    <exercises xml:id="exercises-set-sec-6-2">
	    <title>Exercises: Wire Frames, Partial Derivatives, and Tangent Planes Problems</title>

      <exercisegroup>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            For the given functions and points <m>P_1</m> and <m>P_2</m>:
            <ol marker="(a)">
              <li><p> Give the 2 functions of one variable through <m>P_1</m> obtained by holding each variable constant.</p></li>
              <li><p> Find the partial derivatives of the original function.</p></li>
              <li><p> Evaluate the partial derivatives at <m>P_1</m>.</p></li>
              <li><p> Give the equation of the tangent plane through <m>P_1</m>.</p></li>
              <li><p> The approximation at <m>P_2</m> obtained from the tangent plane.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </introduction>

        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The function is <m>f(x,y)=x^2+3xy+4y^2</m>, <m>P_1=(4,2)</m>, and <m>P_2=(3,2.5)</m>.

              </p>
            </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Give the 2 functions of one variable through <m>P_1</m> obtained by holding each variable constant.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>f(4,y)\amp =16+12y+4y^2</mrow>
                      <mrow>f(x,2)\amp =x^2+6x+16</mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Find the partial derivatives of the original function.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>f_x  (x,y) \amp = 2x+3y</mrow>
                      <mrow>f_y  (x,y) \amp = 3x+8y</mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Evaluate the partial derivatives at <m>P_1</m>.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>f_x  (4,2) \amp = 8+6=14</mrow>
                      <mrow>f_y  (4,2) \amp = 12+16=28</mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Give the equation of the tangent plane through <m>P_1</m>.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    We need <m>f(4,2)=16+24+16=56</m> for the equation of the tangent plane.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>\Linear f(x ,y) \amp = f_x (x_0,y_0 )(x-x_0 )+f_y (x_0,y_0 )(y-y_0 )+f(x_0,y_0 )</mrow>
                      <mrow>\Linear f(x,y) \amp = 14(x-4)+28(y-2)+56</mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    The approximation at <m>P_2</m> obtained from the tangent plane.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>\Linear f(3,2.5) \amp = 14(3-4)+28(2.5-2)+56</mrow>
                      <mrow> \amp =  -14+14+56=56</mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The function is <m>f(x,y)=(x+3y)/(x^2+y^2 )</m>, <m>P_1=(2,3)</m>, and <m>P_2=(3,2.5)</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The function is <m>f(x,y)=(x^2)(x+2^y)</m>, <m>P_1=(3,-1)</m>, and <m>P_2=(3,0)</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Give the 2 functions of one variable through <m>P_1</m> obtained by holding each variable constant.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>f(3,y) \amp = 9(3+2^y)</mrow>
                      <mrow>f(x,-1) \amp = (x^2 )(x+2^{-1} )= x^3+\frac{1}{2} x^2</mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Find the partial derivatives of the original function.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>f_x  (x,y) \amp = (2x)(x+2^y )+(x^2 )(1+0 )  \text{ (product rule)}</mrow>
                      <mrow> \amp =  2x^2+2x 2^y+x^2=3x^2+(2x)2^y</mrow>
                      <mrow>f_y  (x,y) \amp = \frac{\partial}{\partial y} (x^2 )(x+2^y ) \quad (\text{ Take partial derivative wrt }y)</mrow>
                      <mrow> \amp = \frac{\partial}{\partial y}(x^3+x^2 2^y ) \qquad\text{ (Simplify the expression)}</mrow>
                      <mrow> \amp = x^2 2^y  \ln(2)  \qquad  (x \text{ is treated as a constant so the }x^3\text{ term drops out)}</mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Evaluate the partial derivatives at <m>P_1</m>.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>f_x  (3,-1) \amp = 27+(6) 2^{-1}=27+3=30</mrow>
                      <mrow>f_y  (3,-1) \amp =  9*\frac{1}{2}  \ln(2)=\frac{9}{2} \ln(2)</mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Give the equation of the tangent plane through <m>P_1</m>.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    We need <m>f(3,-1)=9*\frac{7}{2}=\frac{63}{2}</m> for the equation of the tangent plane
                    <md>
                      <mrow>\Linear f(x ,y) \amp = f_x (x_0,y_0 )(x-x_0 )+f_y (x_0,y_0 )(y-y_0 )+f(x_0,y_0 )</mrow>
                      <mrow>\Linear f(x ,y) \amp = 30 (x-3)+\frac{9}{2}  \ln(2) (y+1)+\frac{63}{2}</mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    The approximation at <m>P_2</m> obtained from the tangent plane.
                    <me>\Linear f(3,0)=30* (0)+\frac{9}{2} \ln(2) *(1)+\frac{63}{2}=\frac{9}{2}  \ln(2)+\frac{63}{2}</me>.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The function is the revenue function for selling widgets and gizmos with demand price functions
              <md>
                <mrow>\PriceGizmo \amp = 30-\frac{\QuantityGizmo}{50}-\frac{\QuantityWidget}{300}</mrow>
                <mrow>\PriceWidget \amp = 20-\frac{\QuantityWidget}{40}-\frac{\QuantityGizmo}{500}</mrow>
              </md>,
              and <m>P_1=(\QuantityGizmo,\QuantityWidget)=(1000,500)</m>, and <m>P_2=(1050,575)</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The function is the revenue function for selling widgets and gizmos with demand price functions
              <md>
                <mrow>\PriceGizmo \amp = 30(0.95)^{(\QuantityGizmo/100)}-\frac{\QuantityWidget}{300}</mrow>
                <mrow>\PriceWidget \amp = 20(0.9)^{(\QuantityWidget/150)}-\frac{\QuantityGizmo}{250}</mrow>
              </md>,
              and <m>P_1=(\QuantityGizmo,\QuantityWidget)=(800,400)</m>, and <m>P_2=(750,425)</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              For the sake of notation we will use the following abbreviations:
              <md>
                <mrow>\PG \amp = 30(0.95)^{\left(\frac{\QG}{100}\right)}-\frac{\QW}{300}</mrow>
                <mrow>\PW \amp = 20(0.9)^{\left(\frac{\QW}{150}\right)} -\frac{\QG}{250}</mrow>
              </md>,
              and <m>P_1=(\QG,\QW)=(800,400)</m>, and <m>P_2=(750,425)</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
              We need to find the Revenue function to solve the problem:
              <md>
                <mrow>\revenue (\QG,\QW) \amp = \QG*\PG+\QW*\PW</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = \QG\left[30(0.95)^{\left(\frac{\QG}{100}\right)}-\frac{\QW}{300}\right]+\QW\left[20(0.9)^{\left(\frac{\QW}{150}\right)}-\frac{\QG}{250}\right]</mrow>
                <mrow>\revenue(\QG,\QW) \amp =  30 \QG (0.95)^{\left(\frac{\QG}{100}\right)}-\frac{\QG *\QW}{5×6×10}+20 \QW (0.9)^{\left(\frac{\QW}{150}\right)}-\frac{\QG *\QW}{5×5×10}</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp =  30 \QG (0.95)^{\left(\frac{\QG}{100}\right)}+20 \QW (0.9)^{\left(\frac{\QW}{150}\right)}-\frac{11 \QG*\QW}{1500}</mrow>
              </md>.
            </p>

            <p>
              <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Give the 2 functions of one variable through <m>P_1</m> obtained by holding each variable constant.
                    <me>\revenue(800,\QW)= 24,000 (0.95)^8+20 \QW (0.9)^{\left(\frac{\QW}{150}\right)}-\frac{88 \QW}{15}</me>.
                  </p>

                  <p>
                    This function gives us information about the revenue in terns of Widgets near a production level of 400 widgets and 800 gizmos.
                    We can use Wolfram Alpha to graph this. Assuming there are 800 gizmos the widget influence on the revenue looks like this:
                  </p>

                  <image width="60%" source="images/sec6-2-sol5a.png"/>

                  <p>
                    The slope is about <m>m = 4</m>.
                    <me>
                      \revenue(\QG,400)= 30 \QG (0.95)^{\left(\frac{\QG}{100}\right)}+8,000 (0.9)^{\left(\frac{40}{15} \right)}-\frac{44 \QG }{15}
                    </me>.
                  </p>

                  <p>
                    The revenue generated by the gizmos assuming the number of widgets equals 400 and the number of gizmos is near 800 gives the following picture:
                  </p>

                  <image width="70%" source="images/sec6-2-sol5b.png"/>

                  <p>The slope is about <m>m=8</m>.</p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    Find the partial derivatives of the original function.
                  </p>

                  <p>
                    In part a we saw that the revenue function seems to be growing faster for the gizmo variable,
                    then for the widget variable. To get more information we can compute the partial derivatives (b) and then evaluate them at <m>P_1</m> (c).
                    <md>
                      <mrow>\revenue_{\QG}  (\QG,\QW) \amp =  \frac{\partial}{\partial \QG} 30 QG (0.95)^{\left(\frac{\QG}{100}\right)}</mrow>
                      <mrow> \amp \quad +\frac{\partial}{\partial \QG} 20 \QW (0.9)^{\left(\frac{\QW}{150} \right)}-\frac{\partial}{\partial \QG}  \frac{11*\QG*\QW}{1500}</mrow>
                      <mrow> \amp = \left[30 (0.95)^{\left(\frac{\QG}{100}\right)}\right.</mrow>
                      <mrow> \amp  \quad \left.+ 30 \QG (0.95)^{\left(\frac{\QG}{100}\right)}\frac{\ln(0.95)}{100}\right]+0-  \frac{11*\QW}{1500}</mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>

                  <p>
                    Note that the first part requires a product rule and then a chain rule to deal with the exponential part of the formula.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>\revenue_{\QW}  (\QG,\QW)\amp =  \frac{\partial}{\partial \QW} 30 QG (0.95)^{\left(\frac{\QG}{100}\right)}</mrow>
                      <mrow>\amp \quad + \frac{\partial}{\partial \QW} 20 \QW (0.9)^{\left(\frac{QW}{150} \right)}-\frac{\partial}{\partial \QW}  \frac{11*\QG*\QW}{1500}</mrow>
                      <mrow>\amp = 0+\left[20 (0.9)^{\left(\frac{\QW}{150}\right)}+20 \QW (0.9)^{\left(\frac{\QW}{150}\right)}\frac{\ln(0.9)}{150}\right]-  \frac{11*\QG}{1500}</mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    Evaluate the partial derivatives at <m>P_1</m>.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>\revenue_{\QG}  (800, 400) \amp = \left[30 (0.95)^{\left(\frac{800}{100}\right)}+24000 (0.95)^{\left(\frac{800}{100}\right)}\frac{\ln(0.95)}{100}\right]</mrow>
                      <mrow> \amp -  \frac{8800}{1500}\approx 5.86898</mrow>
                      <mrow>\revenue_{\QW}  (800, 400) \amp = \left[20 (0.9)^{\left(\frac{400}{150}\right)}+20 \QW (0.9)^{\left(\frac{400}{150}\right)}\frac{\ln(0.9)}{150}\right]</mrow>
                      <mrow>\amp \quad -  \frac{4400}{1500}\approx 4.99164</mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>

                  <p>The estimates we observed in part a were fairly close to the actual rates of change.</p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    Give the equation of the tangent plane through <m>P_1</m>.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>\Linear \revenue(\QG,\QW) \amp = \revenue_{\QG} (\QG_0,\QW_0 )(\QG-\QG_0 )</mrow>
                      <mrow> \amp \quad + revenue_{\QW} (\QG_0,\QW_0 )(\QW-\QW_0 )+ \revenue(\QG_0,\QW_0 )</mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>

                  <p>
                    We need to find <m>\revenue(800,400)</m>. Using Wolfram Alpha (or calculator) we get
                    <md>
                      <mrow>\revenue(800,400) \amp = 19,615.88</mrow>
                      <mrow>\Linear \revenue(\QG,\QW) \amp = 5.86898(\QG-800)+4.99(\QW-400)+19,615.88</mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    The approximation at <m>P_2</m> obtained from the tangent plane.
                  </p>

                  <p>
                    The estimated revenue when <m>P_2=(750,425)</m> is given by
                    <me>\Linear \revenue(750,425)=5.86898(-50)+4.99(25)+19,615.88=19,300.63</me>.
                  </p>

                  <p>
                    In this case the change in production would result in a loss in revenue.
                    This is mainly due to the impact of the lower production in gizmos.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

