        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The function is the Cobb-Douglas production function in a country,
              <me>\Production(\Labor,\Capital)=10 \Labor^{0.74}\Capital^{0.26}</me>,
              where labor is in millions of workers, capital equipment is in units of billions of dollars,
              and production is in units of billions of dollars per year.
              In the <m>(\Labor,\Capital)</m> plane, let <m>P_1=(300,30)</m>, and <m>P_2=(310,32)</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Give the 2 functions of one variable through <m>P_1</m> obtained by holding each variable constant.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>\Production(300,C) \amp = 10*300^{0.74}  C^{0.26}=680.879 C^{0.26}  </mrow>
                      <mrow>\Production(L,30) \amp = 10 L^{0.74}  30^{0.26}=24.2132 L^{0.74} </mrow>
                    </md>.
                    Hence both cross sections are exponential function.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    Find the partial derivatives of the original function.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>\Production_L  (L,C)\amp =\frac{\partial}{\partial L} 10 L^{0.74}  C^{0.26}</mrow>
                      <mrow>\amp \text{(Take the partial derivative wrt }L\text{; Treat }C\text{ as a constant.)}</mrow>
                      <mrow> \amp =10 (0.74) L^{-0.26}  C^{0.26}</mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>

                  <p>
                    Then we  have
                    <md>
                      <mrow>\Production_L  (L,C) \amp = \frac{7.4 C^{0.26}}{L^{0.26}}</mrow>
                      <mrow>\Production_C  (L,C) \amp = \frac{\partial}{\partial C} 10 L^{0.74}  C^{0.26}</mrow>
                      <mrow>\amp \text{(Take the partial derivative wrt }C\text{; Treat }L\text{ as a constant.)}</mrow>
                      <mrow>\amp =10 L^{0.74} (0.26) C^{-0.74}</mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>

                  <p>
                    Then we  have that
                    <me>\Production_C  (L,C)=2.6 \frac{L^{0.74}}{C^{0.74}}</me>.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    Evaluate the partial derivatives at <m>P_1</m>.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>\Production_L  (300, 30)\amp =\frac{7.4 30^{0.26}}{300^{0.26}} \approx 4.07</mrow>
                      <mrow>\Production_C  (300, 30)\amp =2.6 \frac{300^{0.74}}{30^{0.74}} \approx 14.29</mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    Give the equation of the tangent plane through <m>P_1</m>.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>\Production(300,30)\amp =10*30^{0.74}  30^{0.26}\approx 1648.62</mrow>
                      <mrow>\Linear \Production(L,C) \amp = Prod_L (L_0,C_0 )(L-L_0 )+Prod_C (L_0,C_0 )(C-C_0 )+Prod(L_0,C_0 )</mrow>
                      <mrow> \amp = 4.07(L-300)+14.29(C-30)+1648.62</mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    The approximation at <m>P_2</m> obtained from the tangent plane.
                    <me>
                      \Linear \Production(310, 32)   =4.07(310-300)+14.29(32-30)+1648.62=1717.9
                    </me>.
                  </p>

                  <p>
                    So as both <m>L</m> and <m>C</m> increase, so does the production.
                    Specifically increasing <m>L</m> by 10 million workers and <m>C</m>
                    by 2 billion dollars would give an estimated increase in production of
                    <m>1717.9-1648.62=69.28</m> billions of dollars worth of units.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>

