        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The function is the revenue function for selling widgets, gizmos, and gadgets with demand price functions
              <md>
                <mrow>\PriceGizmo \amp = 30-\frac{\QuantityGizmo}{50}-\frac{\QuantityWidget}{300}-\frac{\QuantityGadget}{500}</mrow>
                <mrow>\PriceWidget \amp = 20-\frac{\QuantityWidget}{40}-\frac{\QuantityGizmo}{500}-\frac{\QuantityGadget}{400}</mrow>
                <mrow>\PriceGadget \amp =40-\frac{\QuantityWidget}{45}-\frac{\QuantityGizmo}{600}-\frac{\QuantityGadget}{300}</mrow>
              </md>,
              and in <m>(\QuantityGizmo,\QuantityWidget,\QuantityGadget)</m> space, <m>P_1=(1000,500,700)</m>, and <m>P_2=(1050,575,625)</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              We can do the entire problem in terms of gadgets, gizmos and widgets,
              but for notation sake we will replace them (alphabetically) as follows:
              <me>x=\text{gadgets},\quad y=\text{gizmos},\quad z=\text{widgets}</me>.
            </p>

            <p>
              We need the revenue function and we have the price functions, so we have that
              <md>
                <mrow>\revenue \amp =R(x,y,z)= x \price_x+y \price_y+z \price_z</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp =x \left(40-\frac{z}{45}-\frac{y}{600}-\frac{x}{300}\right)+y\left(30-\frac{y}{50}-\frac{z}{300}-\frac{x}{500}\right)</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp \quad +z\left(20-\frac{z}{40}-\frac{y}{500}-\frac{x}{400}\right)</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp =  -\frac{x^2}{300}-\frac{11 x y}{3000}-\frac{89 x z}{3600}+40 x-\frac{y^2}{50}-\frac{2 y z}{375}+30 y-\frac{z^2}{40}+20 z</mrow>
              </md>.
            </p>

            <p>(Note: the last step/simplification was done in Wolfram Alpha)</p>

            <p>
              <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Give the 3 functions of one variable through <m>P_1</m> obtained by holding each variable constant.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>R(x,500,700) \amp =  \frac{1}{900}  (-3 x^2+18775 x+8895000)</mrow>
                      <mrow>R(1000,y,700) \amp =  \frac{1}{450}  (-9 y^2+10170 y+9500000)</mrow>
                      <mrow>R(1000,500,z) \amp = \frac{1}{360}  (-9 z^2-2660 z+16140000)</mrow>
                    </md>,
                    so the cross sectional function are all quadratic (parabolas) that open downwards.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Find the partial derivatives of the original function.
                  </p>

                  <p>
                    Finding the partial derivatives when dealing with three variables is very similar to the procedure we use when we have two variables.
                    We treat the other variables as constants.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>R_x  (x,y,z) \amp =   -\frac{x}{150}-\frac{11  y}{3000}-\frac{89  z}{3600}+40 </mrow>
                      <mrow>R_y  (x,y,z) \amp =   -\frac{11 x }{3000}-\frac{y}{25}-\frac{2  z}{375}+30 </mrow>
                      <mrow>R_z  (x,y,z) \amp =  -\frac{89 x }{3600}-\frac{2 y}{375}-\frac{z}{20}+20 </mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    Evaluate the partial derivatives at <m>P_1</m>.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>R_x  (1000,500,700) \amp =   -\frac{1000}{150}-\frac{5500}{3000}-\frac{89  (700)}{3600}+40=\frac{511}{36}</mrow>
                      <mrow>R_y  (1000,500,700) \amp =   -\frac{11000 }{3000}-\frac{500}{25}-\frac{1400}{375}+30=\frac{13}{5}</mrow>
                      <mrow>R_z  (1000,500,700) \amp =  -\frac{89000 }{3600}-\frac{1000 }{375}-\frac{700}{20}+20=-\frac{76}{18}</mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    Give the equation of the linear approximating function through <m>P_1</m>.
                    <me>R(1000,500,700)=\frac{246700}{9}</me>.
                    Then the linear approximation is given by
                    <md>
                      <mrow>\Linear\revenue(x,y,z) \amp = R(1000,500,700)</mrow>
                       <mrow> \amp+R_x  (1000,500,700)  (x-1000)</mrow>
                      <mrow> \amp +  R_y  (1000,500,700)(y-500)</mrow>
                       <mrow> \amp+  R_z  (1000,500,700)(z-700) </mrow>
                      <mrow> \amp =  \frac{246700}{9}+\frac{511}{36} (x-1000)+\frac{13}{5} (y-500)</mrow>
                       <mrow> \amp-\frac{763}{18}(z-700)</mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    The approximation at <m>P_2</m> obtained from the function in d.
                    <md>
                     <mrow>  \Linear\revenue(1050,575,625) =  \frac{246700}{9}+\frac{511}{36} (50)</mrow>
                     <mrow> \amp +\frac{13}{5} (75)-\frac{763}{18} (-75)=31,495</mrow>
                    </md>.
                    <!-- if you have mrows then you need md, not me -->
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>
